What is Metadata?

Metadata is "data about data."

It is hidden information stored within a digital file that describes its properties rather than its visible content.

Common metadata includes:

File Name

File Type

File Size

Date Created

Date Modified

Author

Software Used

Device Information

GPS Coordinates (if available)



---

What is EXIF?

EXIF (Exchangeable Image File Format) is a metadata standard used mainly in photographs captured by smartphones and digital cameras.

EXIF can contain:

Camera Manufacturer

Camera Model

Date & Time Captured

GPS Coordinates

ISO

Aperture

Exposure Time

Flash Information

Image Resolution

Orientation


Not every image contains complete EXIF data, as many social media platforms remove metadata to improve user privacy.


---

Why is Metadata Important?

Metadata helps investigators to:

Verify digital evidence.

Determine when a file was created.

Identify the device used.

Detect edited or modified files.

Discover location information (when available).

Support Digital Forensics investigations.

Assist OSINT investigations.



