      ↓
Check GPS Information (If Available)
      ↓
Cross Verify Findings
      ↓
Document Results


---

Challenges

While performing metadata analysis, investigators may face:

Missing EXIF data

Metadata removed by social media platforms

Edited or manipulated metadata

Missing GPS information

Different outputs from different tools


These challenges highlight why verification is a fundamental part of every OSINT investigation.


---

Best Practices

Analyze only authorized or publicly available files.

Use multiple metadata extraction tools.

Cross-verify findings before drawing conclusions.

Respect privacy and legal boundaries.

Remember that metadata alone is not conclusive evidence.



---

Key Learnings

By the end of today's learning, I understood that:

Metadata contains valuable hidden information.

EXIF provides technical details about digital photographs.

Different file types store different metadata.

Metadata can reveal timestamps, devices, software, and sometimes locations.

Social media platforms often remove metadata to protect privacy.

Every metadata finding should be verified with additional evidence.



---

Summary

Today's session introduced me to Metadata Analysis (EXIF), one of the most valuable techniques in Open Source Intelligence and Digital Forensics.

Through both theoretical concepts and practical exercises, I learned how hidden metadata can reveal valuable insights about digital files. One of the most interesting exercises involved analyzing one of my own mountain trip photographs. What initially appeared to be just a cherished memory also contained hidden technical details about when and where the photo had been taken, demonstrating the investigative value of metadata.

The biggest takeaway from today's learning is that important evidence is often hidden inside the file itself rather than in what we see on the screen. Effective OSINT investigators know how to extract, verify, and responsibly analyze this hidden information while respecting privacy and ethical guidelines.


